		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>San Francisco</placeName> <date>April 15. 1854</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Friend &#8212; </p>
				<p>I have recd the Books with Steamer<lb/> before last&#44; and I hope by next time<lb/> to be able to send you some money.<lb/>  I have sold of the books thus far<lb/> 2 Bibles at &#36;9&#44; 3 at &#36;12&#8212;10 <persName>D.</persName> letters.<lb/> 2 German P. Books &#38; 1 set Prayer<lb/> Books at &#36;31.  I think you done wrong<lb/> incurring the expense of sending<lb/> the books across the <placeName>Isthmus</placeName>&#44; as people<lb/> generally find it too much to pay<lb/> 50 cts. additional to every pound.  I<lb/> think I have written to you to make<lb/> a notice in the Occident that you have<lb/> sent me out such books&#44; which if you had<lb/> it done&#44; would have assisted to have<lb/> all the books sold till now&#59; as there are<lb/> no doubt people which are unaware that<lb/> I have these books to sell&#44; who would want<lb/> them &#38; might find it out through the Occident.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Now I will at once proceed to give you<lb/> some News&#59; if I can think or know<lb/> of any&#44; as there are but very little of any interest</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>to you at present worthy almost of mention.<lb/> Today is the <date>third day of Pesach</date>&#44; and<lb/> so far the synagogues were well attended&#44;<lb/> and many families&#44; most of them keep it<lb/> &#38; have Mazoes&#59; to give you a proof of<lb/> the general observance&#44; I might only tell<lb/> you that one man has sold &#36;160 worth<lb/> of horse radish necessary to the Ceder<lb/> ceremony.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The Committee appointed to give out<lb/> proposals &#38;c have not as yet determined<lb/> their labors&#59; but it is decided that the<lb/> cost of the building alone would not exceed<lb/> the amt. of &#36;20.00&#8212;&#59; for this money a<lb/> fair building<lb/> can be put up.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I would like you to speak in some laudable<lb/> terms of the &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Young Men&#39;s Debating<lb/> Society</hi>&#8221; in the next number of the Occi&#45;<lb/>&#45;dent.  This Society is only about 6 weeks<lb/> in existence &#38; has already between 30 &#38;<lb/> 40 members&#59; the object of the Society is<lb/> for the improvement in debating in discussing various<lb/> kinds of questions.  The Society is composed<lb/> of young men of our persuasion&#44; but the<lb/> zeal&#44; energy &#38; rivalry&#44; and the interest taken<lb/> &#38; manifested by the young men does really<lb/> honor and reflect great credit upon the Jewish<lb/> young men in <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>.  <persName>Mr.<lb/> S. C. Labatt</persName> is President.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Please give my kind regards to <persName>Mr. M. Allen</persName></p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>and please mention to him that I<lb/> have recd his letter &#38; shall answer it<lb/> soon.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. and Mrs. Roggenburger</persName> request me<lb/> to give their kind regards to you&#44;<lb/> &#38; trusting this may find<lb/> you in the enjoyment of<lb/> good health</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">&#40;Signed&#41;   <persName role="author">Cauffman H. Meyer</persName></p>
				<p>Excuse my bad writing as I</p>
				<p>have written this in great haste.</p>
			
